A user who has administration rights, but does not belong to confluence-administrators group (i.e. is not a super user) cannot modify another users password using remote api, even though they can do so via the GUI. 

This is because when the call is made to 

{code}
changeUserPassword(token, "user", "newpass")
{code}

The function in {{com.atlassian.confluence.rpc.soap.services.UsersSoapService}}

{code}
private boolean canUserAdminister(User currentUser)
    {
        return (GeneralUtil.isSuperUser(currentUser) || permissionManager.hasPermission(currentUser, Permission.ADMINISTER, null));
    }
{code}

is called, however {{permissionManager.hasPermission(currentUser, Permission.ADMINISTER, null))}} always returns false. Therefore any users that are not super users (i.e. belongs to confluence-administrators) even though they have administrator rights, cannot modify a password through remote API. 

The workaround for customers is to add the user to the confluence-administrators group.

