We have noticed an interesting wrinkle with the include macro:

If you include a page from a different space then confluence will continue to think that it is in the included space after the macro has finished running.

We noticed this on adaptavist.com ... where you use an include macro on a page which includes data from a different space the page's layout gets re-set to the one used by the included page .. on checking into the include macro source it would appear that finally blocks are not called if the try block contains a return.

eg:

{noformat}
    protected String fetchPageContent(String spaceKey, String pageTitle, Map parameters, PageContext pageContext)
    {
...
   ContentIncludeStack.push(page);

        try
        {
            return subRenderer.render(page.getContent(), new PageContext(page, pageContext));
        }
        finally
        {
            ContentIncludeStack.pop();
        }
{noformat}

should probably become

{noformat}
...
ContentIncludeStack.push(page);
        String output = "";

        try
        {
            output = subRenderer.render(page.getContent(), new PageContext(page, pageContext));
        }
        finally
        {
            ContentIncludeStack.pop();
        }

        return output;
{noformat}
